{"accepted":[{"assertion":"Hosted Lean proof: plby proof of 291 (state partial) https://github.com/plby/lean-proofs/blob/main/src/v4.29.1/ErdosProblems/Erdos291.lean.","id":"vf_07ae83e9d65441c9","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"},{"assertion":"Erdős Problem #291: declared status 'open'. Formalized: no. Let $n\\geq 1$ and define $L_n$ to be the least common multiple of $\\{1,\\ldots,n\\}$ and $a_n$ by\\[\\sum_{1\\leq k\\leq n}\\frac{1}{k}=\\frac{a_n}{L_n}.\\]Is it true that $(a_n,L_n)=1$ and $(a_n,L_n)>1$ both occur for infinitely many $n$? Current best: There is in fact a necessary and sufficient condition: a prime $p\\leq n$ divides $(a_n,L_n)$ if and only if $p$ divides the numerator of $1+\\cdots+\\frac{1}{k}$, where $k$ is the leading digit of $n$ in base $p$. Prize: no. OEIS: A110566. Tags: number theory, unit fractions.","id":"vf_3b9cd542fd44ba79","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"},{"assertion":"Formal-Conjectures statement: Erdos291.erdos_291.variants.shiu_heuristic_density_zero https://google-deepmind.github.io/formal-conjectures/theorem/?name=Erdos291.erdos_291.variants.shiu_heuristic_density_zero.","id":"vf_feba19557e63cf71","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"}],"accepted_activity":false,"activity":[],"activity_types":[],"attempt_count":0,"banked_attempt_count":0,"commits":[],"dependency_impact":"none","detail_url":"problems/291.json","draft_proposals":[],"edges":[{"evidence":"Problem identity derived from the accepted finding's pinned source anchor.","inferred":true,"relation":"describes","source":"vf_07ae83e9d65441c9","source_root":"sha256:1faedc24f040a60a22177b456c74b969a61ce8836082297b1835797a57b4fa56","target":"erdos:291","trust":"signed"},{"evidence":"Materialized typed link between accepted findings.","inferred":true,"relation":"supports","source":"vf_07ae83e9d65441c9","source_root":"sha256:1faedc24f040a60a22177b456c74b969a61ce8836082297b1835797a57b4fa56","target":"vf_3b9cd542fd44ba79","trust":"signed"},{"evidence":"Problem identity derive